    "Training Strategy": "Sampling: Latin hypercube or quasi-random sampling for interior collocation points, denser near walls to capture multiple reflections. Boundary points: distributed along maze walls according to their curvature, with higher density at corners. PML region points follow a stretched coordinate rule. Loss: weighted sum of PDE, BC, and PML residuals; weights tuned by dynamic balancing (e.g., learning rate annealing or gradient normalization). Optimizer: Adam with scheduled learning rate decay, possibly followed by L-BFGS for fine-tuning. To avoid local minima, training restarts with different weight initializations. Validation: since no reference data exist, rely on physical consistency checks: compute the energy flux integral over a closed surface to verify energy conservation (difference with incident power should match absorption at impedance walls), check reciprocity by swapping source and receiver locations (if applicable), and examine the convergence of the PDE residual on a dense test set not used in training. Furthermore, a separate PINN trained on a simplified single-scatterer problem with known analytic solution ensures the framework is correct before maze deployment.",
